{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_junco_ver01/data/sn83045499/00514154442/1949061401/1018.xml":{"full_text":"Daily Alaska Empire\nPublished every evening except Sunday by the\nI MPIRK PRINTING COMPANY\nSecond and Main Streets. Juneau. Alaska\nHELEN TROY MONSFN\nDOROTHY TROY LINGO\nELMER A FRIEND\nALFRED ZENGER\nPresiden.\nVice-President\nManaging Editor\nBusiness Manager\nEntered in the Post Office In Juneau as Second Class Matter\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES:\nDelivered b> carrier in Juneau and Douglas for SI.50 per month)\nsix months- *8 PO; one year, *15.PA\nBy mall, postage paid, at the following rates:\nOne year. In advance. 115.00; six months. In advance, 17.50\n\u00bbne month. In advance. #1 50.\nSubscribers will confer a favor If they will promptly notify\nthe Business Office of any failure or irregularity In the delivery\ntf their papers.\nTelephones: News Office, 602: Business Office, 374.\nMEMBER OF ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to the use for\n'evubJ'cation of all news dispatches credited to It or not other\nwise jredw ^A in this paper and also the local news published\nl?reln.\nNATIONAL REPRESENTATIVES Alaska Newspapers. 1411\nNxiith Avenue Bids.. Seattle, Wash.\ny i\nBUSINESS JITTERS\nThe sinking spell during recent days of stock\nmarket prices coincident with a further drcp in steel\noutput and in grain and other commodity prices brings\npredictions of worse to come. Yet an objective ex\namination of current price and production indices does\nnot seem to warrant pessimism about the business\noutlook. The fear of a slump rivaling that of the\nthirties or the sharp price collapse that fullowea\nWorld War I appears to be based on the assumption\nthat because past booms have been followed by busts\nthe cycle is certain to be repeated. This is as super\nficial a judgment as the belief that the country can\nbe safeguarded against future setbacks by Govern\nment price supports and the stimulative effect of\nGovernment spending.\nUndoubtedly the price downturn has failed so far\nto stimulate an expansion of buying to the extent\nhoped for. That is due to a considerable extent, how\never, to a widespread belief that further declines lie j\nhead. As a result many industrial buyers have been\nfollowing a cautious hand-to-mouth buying policy,\nlimiting the volume of new orders and working off\ninventories of high-priced goods. That practice leads\nto reductions in manufacturing operations, and con\nsequent dismissals, layoffs and part-time employment\nfor factory workers.\nAlthough lack of confidence in the stability of\nthe price structure has accelerated the current busi\nness downturn, the situation today differs in important\nrespects from that prevailing at the beginning of\nprevious major depressions. For instance, the Federal\nReserve Board reports that the value of department\nstore sales increased more than seasonally in April and\nthe first half of May. Allowing for the later date\nof Easter this year, sales were only 3 per cent below\nthe high level of a year ago. Furthermore, since\nretail prices are somewhat lower, unit sales of goods\nshowed little change compared with a year ago.\nApparently recent drops in stock is just a matter\nof business speculation and that is all, and we\u2019ll sit\ntight and watch the outcome.\nReading Is Reading\n(Cincinnati Enquirer)\nThat awful phrase, \u201csummer reading.\u201d and its\ntwin, \"hammock reading,\u201d are beginning to find their\nway baek into print now that the peonies and jellied\nconsomme l.ave appeared on the scene. The publishers\nhave thinned their lists and lightened the fare. The\nNew York Times is sponsoring a drive (we know not\nhowi to induce people to read more books during the\nsummer season.\nIt is our contention, based on no statistics what\never, but on observation, that ueonle are aDt to read\nmore in summer than they do in winter if for no other\n\u2019\u2022eason than that they have a little more time. Many\na person, instead of succumbing to hammock literature,\nso-called, sets himself a stiff reading chore for his\nvacation: Toynbee, or the first two volumes of Chur\nchill\u2019s war memories, \"Jean Christophe,\u201d the novels\nof Jane Austen or \u201cWar and Peace.\u201d Something he\n>an dig his teeth into, he tells himself. Sometimes he\nfinds that, his eyes have been bigger than his teeth,\nand he therefore mav have switched to Erie Stanley\nGardner before he has completed his self-assigned\nrhore.\nBut his intentioas have been of the loftiest and,\nit the outset, at least, he has not flinched before the\nidea of tackling something \u201cheavy.\u201d Hot or cold, ham\nhock or armchair, reading is reading, and the more\nof it the better.\nIt\u2019s a cinch in this country for any handsome\ncandidate with pleasing manners, a charming voice\nand the name of Roosevelt to win an election.\nThe Washington\nMerry-Go-Round\nBy DREW PEARSON\n(Continued Irom Page 1)\ntrol all north and central China,\nGen. Mao Tse-tung sent word to\nRussia that he wanted to take over\nthe Chinese half of Dairen.\nWhereupon the Russians said no.\nThey said it emphatically and they\nhaye refused to budge since.\nAs a result Mao Tse-tung and\nChinese Communist leaders are\nboiling mad. They have come to\nbeheve that under the much-vaunt\ned Russian-Communist system,\nChina may not have as much land\nas she did under the old-fashioned\ncapitalists.\nBARKLEY\u2019S SON-IN-LAW\nWashington\u2019s sanctimonious news\nmen say it shouldn\u2019t be written\nabout, merely be buzzed about at\nWashington dinner tables. However,\none of the political misfortunes of\nWashington is the manner in which\nthe Vice President\u2019s son-in-law,\nMax Truitt, is cashing in on Alben\nBarkley\u2019s fine name.\nTruitt is an able, likeable law\npartner of ex-Attorney General Ho\nmer Cummings. Both get plenty of\nlaw practice on their own. How\never, since his father-in-law be\ncame Vice President of the United\nStates, Truitt\u2019s law business has\nexpanded so the clients almost jos\ntle each ether getting inside the\ndoor.\nIn addition, young Truitt is not\ntoo selective. On his list are the\nthree chief dictators of the Latin\nworld\u2014Franco of Spain, Trujillo of\nthe Dominican Republic, and indi\nrectly, through the largest Argen\ntine shipping company, Peron of\nArgentina.\nIn fairness to the Vice President,\nit should be noted that he is fre\nquently on the opposite side of the\nfence from his son-in-law. When\nTruitt was retained by the tidelands\noil lobby, Barkley fought on the\nSenate floor to kill the tidelands\noil bill. Also, when Truitt regis\ntered as the paid agent of Dictator\nFranco and lobbied for his full\nrecognition. Barkley was known pri\nvately to oppose such recognition.\nAT WHITE HOUSE DINNERS\nMeanwhile, Truitt gets in on some\nof the most inner circle parties in\nWashington -thanks to the fact\nthat his wife is official hostess for\nthe Vice President, The White\nHouse dinner for Winston Churchill\nwas one of the most exclusive ever\nthrown by the Trumans. Not even\nSenators Tom Connally and Arthur\nVandenberg, cn whom the President\nmust depend for his bipartisan\nforeign policy, were invited\nBut lawyer-lobbiest Max Truitt\nwas.\nIGNORING STARS AND STRIPES\nLatest of Max's operations has\nbeen to demand that the Maritime\nCommission permit Standard Oil of\nNew Jersey to transfer six modern\noil tankers to the Panamanian flag.\nThe Mar.time Commission had re\nfused to do this for Standard Oil,\nso Standard then hired the versatile\nMax. The Commission's refusal\nwas based on the fact that oil is\ngetting scare in this country and,'\nin time of war, the nation's entire\neconomy will depend on having\nenough tankers to bring in foreign\noil. If the tankers are under a\nforeign flag, however, the United\nStates loses contrci.\nBut since operation under the\nPanamanian flag means less taxes\nand lower wages, Max Truitt went\nto bat for Standard Oil. He pro\nposed that Standard Oil register\nunder the Panamanian flag six\nmodern tankers built since 1942;\nand threatened that, if this was not\naccepted by the Maritime Commis\ns;cn, four tankers now building\nwould not be registered under the\n1 Stars and Stripes.\n\"The Standard Oil Company,\u201d\nwrote Truitt, ''will have (four)\nI tankers which it desires to place\nunder American llag and registry,\n'to be manned with citizen person\n-el, provided it is permitted to\nj transfer to Panamanian flag and\n'registry the equivalent carrying\ncapacity of used tankers.\n\"The company therefore suggests,\u201d\ncontinued Truitt, \"that the Com\nmission reconsider its action\nby which it declined to approve the\napplication to transfer to foreign\nflag and registry the vessels above\nnamed, and desires to point out\nthat (otherwise) this will re\nsult in the loss of the newer tank\ners to the American Merchant Ma\nrine and the national defense pro\ngram.\u201d\nThe .Vice President\u2019s son-in-law\nused to be general counsel of the\nMaritime Commission, later was a\nfull-fledged commissioner. Never\ntheless, his former colleagues did\nnot relish Max\u2019s squeeze play re\ngarding oil tankers.\nPENSION PREDICTIONS\nThose interested in higher pen\nsions and more social security\nbenefits can figure that it\u2019s a sale\nprediction Congress will split SO\nSO with President Truman on his\nplea to put 20,000,000 more people\non Social Security rolls. In other\nI words, Congress will cut the figure\nto 10,000,000.\nThe 10,000,000 new Social Security\nbeneficiaries will include self-em\nployed workers (salesmen number\ning almost 7,009,0001, permanent do\nmestic servants and ether smaller\nemployee groups.\nOn the other hand, Truman's re\nquest for inclusion of all types of\nfarm employees, members of the\narmed services and casual domes\ntic servants will be rejected.\nThe pension retirement age will\nbe kept at 65 years for men, but\ndropped to 60 for women.\nHottest controversy when the1\nWays and Means Committee starts j\nvoting behind closed doors on Tru- j\nman\u2019s Social Security reforms will J\nbe over his request that minimum\npensions for retired workers with\ndependents be raised from $10 a 1\nmonth to $25 and that maximum I\npensions be raised frem $82.50 to\n$150.\nInsiders believe the minimum $25 t\npension will be voted, but that the I\nnew maximum pension will be clcs- I\ner to $100 than $150.\nTo help finance these benefits.\nthe present aggregate payroll tax j\nof 2 per cent on employer and em- I\nployee will be raised to 3 per cent\n(that is, \u2018,i per cent additional on j\nboth employer and employee# el-1\nfective January 1, 1950.\nSCHWINN BIKES at M/ibSEN\u2019S.\nJeannette Doucette\nAnd Chas. McLeod\nIn June Ceremonies\nWedding vows were spoken Sat\nurday evening at 8 o\u2019clock by Miss\nJeannette Doucette, daughter of Mr.\nand Mrs. Charles Doucette, and\nj Mr. Charles McLeod, son of Mrs. H.\nMcLeod, at the Catholic Church\nI with the Rev. Leo H. Sweeney offi\nelating.\nMiss Doucette was dressed in a\ni royal blue suit with white accessor\nies and a corsage of pink roses. Her\nattendant, Cpl. Myriam Schell,\nWAAF, and the best man, Lawrence\nSwanson, both wore their Armed\nForces uniforms.\nThe bride was given in marriage\nby her father. Mrs. Doucette wore\nan attractive navy blue suit with\nwhite accessories.\nA reception at the home of the\nbiide\u2019s parents followed the cere\nmony, with Mrs. Frank Olson and\nMrs. Peter Oswald as assisting host\nesses.\nHOSPITAL NOTES\nAdmitted to St. Ann's hospital\nyesterday were William Wallace,\nMarian Glafke and John Hopen.\nDischarged from: Mrs. Roger\nAltman, Troy Walker and Harold\nHanson.\nDischarged from the Government\nhospital were Mary Peterson and\nIfcaby girl of Mt. Edgecumbe.\nTire first centralized indus\ntry was in New Amsterdam, on\nManhattan, whose handmade glass\nware was manufactured continu\nously frem 1646 to 1767.\nrossword Puzzle\nACROSS\nL Peer (lynt's\nmother\n4. Ooze\n9. Self\n12. Eased\n14. Moving truck\n15. Word indicat*\ning choice\n16. Feminine\nname\n17. Exact likeness\n19. Plentiful\n21. Music studies\n22. Employs\n20. Change\n2;\u00bb. Anchor rings\n27. Debatable\n2S. Italian river\n20. Consumed\nSi. Country in\nArabia\n33. Bullfinch\n34. Exclamation\n35. Land measure\n36. Frolic\n38. Slopes\n40. Not fat\n41. Grew to be\n43. Collect\n45. Town In Maine\n46. Ardor\n47. Aloft\n49. Term of\nrespect\n50. Collection\n53. Fowl\n54. Adversary\n55. Charge\nDOWN\n1. Philippine 3.\nvolcano 4.\n2. Town in\nFlorida 5.\nSolution of Yesterday\u2019! Puzzle\nDutch meter\nFoundation\ntimber\nMore crippled\n6. City In\nParaguay\n7. Myself\n8. issues\n9. Escape by\nartifice\n10. Kind of plum\n11. Units\n13. Slip\nIS. 18 compelled to\n20. Nothing mor#\nthan\n21. Bacchanalian\ncry\n22. Western stats\n24. Ant\n26. Plane tree\n25. Enjoyment\n2!). Begin\n32. Sea eagle\n33. Metal-bearing\nrocks\n35. Masculine\nname\n37. Vegetable\norganism\n38. Disdain\n39. City in Massa\nchusetts\n41. Humbug\n42. American Inks\n44. English queen\n46. Netherlands\ncommune\n48. Father of\nmodern en\ngraving\n51. Type measure\n52. About\nJUNE 14\nThomas A. Morgan, Jr.\nBrice Mielke\nDoris June Graves\nWilliam Byington\nMrs. P- S. Bowen\nClarice Donlay\nMrs. Fred Haugen\nR. T. Scott\nACTING GOVERNOR\nCLEARS ANY DOUBTS\nABOUT WELFARE FUNDS\nBelieving that a former public\nservant has been maligned, at least\nby inference, Acting Governor Lev.\nM. Williams today made a state\nment of special interest to reader.\ncf two ether Alaska newspapers.\nAn editorial titled \u201cComing Out\nIn Open,\u201d which originated in the\nFairbanks-Miner and was reprinted\nin the Ketchikan Daily News, is the\nbasis for his comment. This edi\ntorial places Russell Maynard, for\nmer director of the Alaska Depart\nment of Public Welfare, in the\ncompany of other Territorial offi\ncials in whose offices have been\nfound irregularities in the handling\nof public funds.\nThe acting governor has this to\nsay:\n\"As far as Russell Maynard and\nhis office are concerned, everything\nwas in A-l order, and complied\nfully with the laws pertaining to\npublic welfare and to the regula\ntions established by his board.\n\"The board itself, before accepting\nhis resignation, had two cf the au\nditors now conducting the Territor\nial audit cover the accounts of the\nPublic Welfare office. They stat\ned to the board liiat they found\neverything in order and as it should\nbe.\n\"At no time during the eight\nyears of Mr. Maynard's tenure in\noffice, has there been any question\nrelating to the accuracy of his ac\ncounts.\n\"Personal differences between Mr.\nMaynard and certain members of\nthe Legislature, and certain mem\nbers of the board prompted his\nresignation. He felt that, in view\nof this personal criticism, it would\nbe best to step aside after his\nlong tenure of office.\"\ni k r.\nTIDE TABLE\nJUNE 15\nHigh tide, 4:24 a.m., 15,5 ft.\nLow tide, 11:08 a.m., -0.4 ft.\nHigh tide, 17:37 p.m., 13.9 ft.\nLow tide, 23:25 p.m., 4.8 ft.\nWARREN GRANT IS\nGRADUATE OF AIFT\nAmong the 185 students gradu\ni ating Saturday, June 4, from the\nj American Institute for Foreign\nI Trade near Phoenix, Ariz., was\nWarren B. Grant, son of Mr. and\nMrs. Leigh S. Grant of Douglas.\nAn intensive year's course ol\ngraduate work in the Spanish lan\nguage, area study, and training in\nthe practices and techniques oi\nforeign commerce has prepared\nhim for a career in foreign trade.\nA graduate of Grass Valley High\nSchool in California, he attended\nTexas Tech at Lubbock, Texas, and\nSan Jose State in San Jose, Cali\nfornia.\nGlassware made in 1609 at the\nJamestown, Va., factory was the\nfirst made-in-America article to\nbe exported.\nV\n20 YEARS AGO ?he empire\nJUNE 14, 1929 I\nJohn B. Marshall, Mendenhall fox farmer and ice cream manu\nfacturer, gave a brief and interesting address at the traditional Flag\nDay exercises, which were attended by a record crowd. Mrs. E. M.\nGoddard gave a history of the flag and Miss Evelyn Judson sang, ac\ncompanied by Miss Gladys Naghel. A last-minute feature of the pro\ngram was the singing of Laurence A. Lambert, manager of the West\nminster Glee Club. Mrs. Fern Vance accompanied him.\nMiss Isabelle Meehan of Tacoma was a guest for the week of Miss\nMamie Feusi of Douglas, who had entertained in her honor. The young\nwomen had attended the same college, and worked for the same Tacoma\nfirm.\nMrs. Charles Fox of Douglas gave a bridge luncheon at which Mrs.\nCharles Rice and Mrs. Charles Sey took the prizes.\nRaymond Haines, who had left the day before on a second try to\nbeat the steamer time to Seattle in his outboard motored 15-foot boat,\nwas on the second leg of the trip, having left Ketchikan after his first\nday\u2019s run.\nMiss Grace Naghel returned from Cheney, Wash., where she had\ncompleted her teacher\u2019s training work at the State Normal School.\nShe was to teach in the Seattle primary schools in the fall.\nZ. J. Loussac, druggist of Anchorage and formerly of Juneau, was\nin town briefly while the Alaska was in port.\nWeather: High, 56; low, 46; cloudy.\nDaily Lessons in English w. l. Gordon\nWORDS OFTEN MISUSED: Do not say, \"Two and two is four.\u201d\nSay, \"Two and two ARE four.\u201d \u201cTwo PLUS two IS four\u201d is correct.\nOFTEN MISPRONOUNCED: Licorice. Pronounce lik-o-RIS, and not\nlik-o-RISH.\nOFTEN MISSPELLED: Irritable; two R's. Iridescent; one R.\nSYNONYMS: Previous, preceding, prior, former, foregoing, ante\ncedent.\nWORD STUDY: \"Use a word three times and it is yours.\u201d Let us\nincrease our vocabulary by mastering one word each day. Today\u2019s word:\nLINGUAL; pertaining to the tongue, or use of the tongue in utterance.\n\u201cThere were lingual difficulties in her speech.\u201d\nMODERN ETIQUETTE ROBERTA lee\nQ. Should one take small bites when eating?\nA. Yes. The bite should never be so large that it is difficult to\nanswer a question immediately, without the neecssity of first chewing\nand swallowing.\nQ. When giving a graduation present, should it be presented at the\nexercise?\nA. No; the gift should be given within a month preceding the\ngraduation exercises.\nQ. If a man has a title, such as doctor or professor, does his wife\nshare it?\nA. No.\nr l\nLOOK and LEARN c. GORDON\n1. What seven States of the U. S. have an area of more than 100,000\nsquare miles?\n2. How many standard cups of water are there in a gallon?\n3. What lawyer wrote the words of our national anthem?\n4. What is the capital city of Finland\n5. In what river was Jesus baptized?\nANSWERS:\n1. Texas, California, Montana, New Mexico, Arizona, Nevada, and\nColorado.\n2. Sixteen.\n3. Francis Scott Key.\n4. Helsingfors.\n5. The River Jordan.\nPlumbing Heating\nOil Burners\nTelephone-319 Nighls-Red 730\nHarri Machine Shop* Inc.\nOldest Bank in Alaska\n1891\u2014Over Half a Century of Banking\u20141949\nThe B. HI. Kell rends\nBank\nSafety Deposit\nBoxes for Rent\nCOMMERCIAL SAVINGS\nSHERMAN SMITH\nas a paid-up subscriber to THE J1AILY ALASKA\nEMPIRE is invited to be our guest THIS EVENING\nPresent this coupon to the box office of the\nCAPITOL THEATRE\nand receive TWO TICKETS to see:\n'THE PIRATE\"\nFederal Tax\u201412c\u2014Paid by the Theatre\nPhone 14\u2014YELLOW CAB CO.\u2014Phone 22\nand an insured cab WILL CALL FOR YOU and\nRETURN YOU to your home with our compliments.\nWATCH THIS SPACE\u2014Your Name May Appear!\nWOMEN BOTANISTS\nLEAVE ON MONTH'S\nTRIP TO INTERIOR\nOff for a month\u2019s botanical ex\npedition to collect Alaskan speci\nmens for the Juneau Botanical\nClub herbarium, and for noted\nbotanists stateside, are four local\nwomen.\nMrs. Harry Stonehouse, Mrs. V.\nF. Williams and Miss Christine\nHeller left aboard the Denali on\nMonday far Haines to be joined\nby Mrs. J. O. Rude who plans to\nfly to Haines tomorrow.\nThey plan to drive their car,\nshipped to Haines aboard the\nDenali, over the Haines Cut-off\nand the Alaska Highway to the\nInterior.\nAlthough the women have gone\non individual botanizing trips be\nfore, this is their first try at an\nextended field trip. There will be\nno hotel living for the travelers\nduring their tour. They plan to\ncamp out for the month.\nFrom Fairbanks they plan to go\nto Circle and Livingood and then\nback to Fairbanks to take off for\nValdez with a side trip to Chitna.\nAt Tok Junction they will cut off\nto Nebesna and then return to\nTok to return down the highway\nto Haines.\nMrs. Williams, who is preparing\na book on Alaska wild flowers for\npublication, will gather material for\nher manuscript, including camera\nshots of Alaskan flowers for illus\ntrating purposes.\nRequests for botanical informa\ntion on Alaska have come from Dr.\nEric Hulton of Sweden, Dr. J. P.\nAnderson of Iowa, Dr. Carleton\nBall of Washington, D.C., and Dr.\nFlorence Paulser of the University\nof Chicago. Juneau\u2019s women\nbotanists will gather information to\nforward to these scientists on their\nreturn.\nSCHWINN BIKES at MADSEN\u2019S.\nGEORGE BHOS.\nWidest Selection of\nMQUORS\nPHONE 399\n\u201cSay It With Flowers\u201d but\n\u201cWAY IT WITH OURS!\u201d\nJuneau Florists\nPHONE 111\nThe Erwin Feed Ce.\nOffice Is Caae Lot Grocery\n/HONE 7M\nHAY, GRAIN, COAL\nand STORAGE\nCaU EXPERIENCED MEN\nAla*a JANITORIAL Service\nFRED FOLETTE\nPhone 247\nSTEVENS\u2019\nLADIES\u2019\u2014MISSES\u2019\nREADY-TO-WEAR\nSeward Street Near Third\nThe Charles W. Carter\nMortuary\nFourth and Franklin Sta\nPHONE US\nCard Beverage Ce.\nWholesale SOB 10th BL\nPHONE ns\u2014DAT er NIGHT\nfor MIXERS er SODA POT\nCaller's Men's Wear\nFormerly SABOTS\nBOTANY\n\"500\"\nCLOTHES\nNUNN-BUSH SHOES\nSTETSON HATS\nQuality Work Clothing\nFRED HENNING\nCwnf lets Outfitter tor Men\n1. W. COWLING\nCOMPANY\nBHArrnro\nSANITARY MEAT\nIOB BBTTUt HUTS\nIS\u2014PHONES\u20144*\nMOUNT JUNEAU LODGE NO. Uf\nSECOND and FOURTH\nMonday of eat*, month\nin Scottish Rite Temple\nbeglnlng at 7:30 p. m.\nOLENN O. ABRAHAM,\nWorshipful Master;\nJAMES W. LEIVERS, Secretary.\n0 B.P.O.ELKS\nMeeting every Wednesday at\n8 P. M. Visiting brothers wel\ncome. F. DEWEY BAKER,\nExalted Ruler. W. H. BIOOS,\nSecretary.\nBLACKWELL\u2019S\nCABINET SHOP\n17 Main St. Phone 772\nHigh Quality Cabinet Work\nfor Home, Office or Store\n\nNoose Lodge No. 700\nRegular Meetings Each Friday\nGovernor\u2014JOHN LADELY\nSecretary\u2014\nWALTER R. HERMANSEN\nBert's Food Center\nGrocery Phone* 1*4\u2014irs\nMoot Phone* 39\u2014539\nDeliveries\u201410:15 A. M.\n3:15 4:00 P. M.\n\u201cThe Rexall Store\"\nTour Reliable Ph&mucWi\nBUTLER-MAURO\ndrug ca\nAlaska Music Supply\nArthur M- Uggen, Manager\n\u00ab\u00abw\u00bbr#&leal InstruMate\nSeward\nWQU Paper\nIdnkl Paint Shop\nJuneau\u2019s Finest\nLiquor Store\nBAVABD'S\nPhone 689\nThe Alaskan Haiti\nNewly IimtiM fiiW\nM BwumUi Iiih\nraoNi UNGU O\n-_\n'-.I x\nPHONE 655\nThomas Hardware Co.\nPAINTS OILS\nMUnTuiiM\nHARDWARE\n\u25a0^Typewriters\nJ. B.fliJricrd&V..\n\"Ow Dowitep b worn by\nFORD AGENCY\n(Authorised Dealer.)\nGREASES GAS OIL\nJnnean Motor Co.\nFoot of Mala Street\nJUNEAU DAIRIES\nDELICIOUS ICE CREAM\ndaily habit\u2014ufc far tt by mum\nJuneau Dairies, Inc.\nChrysler Marine Engines\nMACHINE SHOP\nMarine Hardware\nChas. G. Warner Co.\nHOME GROCERY\nPhone 146\nTo Banish \u201cBlue Monday\u201d\nTo give you more freedom\nfrom work TRY\nAlaska Laundry\nDR. ROBERT SIMPSON\nOPTOMETRIST\nByee Gl.f rtttei\nSIMPSON BUILDINO\nPhone 386 for Appatntmante\nH. S. GRAVES\nThe Clothing M..\nLEVPS OVERALLS\nfor Boys","height":"26664","width":"20928"}}
